Chapter 3: The Humming Gate
The Academy was unnaturally quiet. Most students were in the dorms, obsessively checking their gear for tomorrow's Field Training. Ren, however, stood in the service corridor of Basement Level 4. The air here was different—thick, cold, and tasting of copper.
"I told you, kid. It’s been singing for three days."
The janitor, a hunched man known only as Silas, leaned against a rusted steam pipe. He wasn't looking at Ren; he was staring at the heavy, blast-proof door that led to the "Dormant Gate."
"The sensors on the main floor say it’s flatline," Ren said, holding up a mechanical diagnostic tool. The needle was dead still, but the casing of the device was vibrating so hard it blurred.
"Sensors," Silas spat, a wet, rattling sound. "The Association builds sensors to find what they want to find. You don't need a Rank to hear that, do you?"
Ren went quiet. He pressed his ear against the cold metal of the door. It wasn't a sound, exactly. It was a low-frequency thrum that felt like it was trying to untie his DNA.
"It sounds like... breathing," Ren whispered.
"Fast breathing," Silas corrected. "Like something’s running a race. Here." He handed Ren a heavy, industrial-grade wrench. "The manual override for the elevator is behind that panel. Fix it and get out. Don't look at the monitors in the sub-vault."
"Why?"
"Because the monitors don't show the room," Silas said, pushing off the pipe and walking toward the stairs. "They show the basement as it was fifty years ago. Before the school was built. If you see people on those screens, Ren... they aren't there."
Ren watched the old man disappear into the shadows of the stairwell. He turned to the panel, his fingers moving mechanically. He unscrewed the bolts, his mind racing.
"Ren? What are you doing down here?"
He jumped, nearly dropping the wrench. Mira stood at the end of the hall, her shadow elongated by the flickering overhead lights. She looked small, her Academy blazer buttoned all the way to her chin.
"Instructor Graves’ orders," Ren said, his pulse slowing. "The elevator. Why aren't you in the dorms?"
"I couldn't sleep," she stepped closer, her eyes darting to the Gate door. "My ears won't stop ringing. Jax and the others... they’re celebrating. They think tomorrow is just a trophy hunt. But the resonance in the air... it feels like the Sector 7 Breach. Only closer."
Ren pulled the panel open. Behind it wasn't just wires. A thick, black substance—like hardened tar—was oozing between the circuits.
"Mira, look at this."
She leaned in, then recoiled. "Is that... Void-leak? Inside the school?"
"It’s not supposed to be physical," Ren muttered, poking the substance with the wrench. It didn't stick; it recoiled from the metal, almost like a living muscle. "The textbooks say the Void is a state of energy, not matter."
"Maybe the textbooks are wrong," Mira whispered. She looked at Ren, her expression desperate. "Ren, you’re the only one who actually reads the technical logs. The missing students from last year—the ones they said 'transferred'—did they all have their Field Training at the same site we’re going to?"
Ren hesitated. He thought about the files he’d scavenged from the library’s trash cache. "Site 9. Every single one of them."
"That’s where we’re going tomorrow," she said.
The lights in the corridor flickered once, twice, and then stayed off. In the sudden pitch black, the humming from behind the Gate door spiked. It wasn't a low thrum anymore; it was a shriek that only existed inside their heads.
Ren felt the metal disc in his pocket turn searing hot.
"Ren! I can't hear anything!" Mira screamed, though her voice sounded miles away.
A faint, green light began to bleed through the cracks of the Gate door. Not the green of a sensor, but a sickly, pale phosphor.
"Get to the stairs, Mira! Go!" Ren grabbed her arm, shoving her toward the exit.
"What about you?"
"I have to lock the override! If the elevator stays open, whatever is making that noise is going straight to the dorms!"
Ren didn't wait for her answer. He lunged for the manual lever, buried deep in the black, tar-like sludge. As his hand submerged in the cold, oily mass, the world didn't go dark—it went white.
A voice, cold and synthesized, echoed not in the room, but in the marrow of his bones:
[Primary User: UNKNOWN]
[Status: 0.00% Affinity Detected]
[Condition Met: The Vessel is Empty.]
Ren gasped, pulling his hand back. The black sludge was gone. The lights flickered back on. The hallway was silent. Mira was gone, likely having bolted for the stairs.
Ren looked at his palm. There was no oil. No burn. Just a small, glowing '0' that faded into his skin.
His handheld scanner, sitting on the floor, suddenly buzzed to life. It didn't show the elevator diagnostics. It showed a single line of text:
[Objective: Attend Field Training. Destination: Site 9.]
That concludes our "Pre-System" setup. The mystery is set, the world is established through the characters, and the "Logic" of the world is beginning to break.
